From: PS3 Custom Toolchain
Subject: [PATCH] rs6000: pick TLS base register from ELF class, not pointer mode

Patch 0016 retargeted the local-exec, rs6000_tls_size==32 branch of
rs6000_legitimize_tls_address from TARGET_64BIT to Pmode == DImode.
That move was correct for choosing between the gen_tls_tprel_ha_64
and gen_tls_tprel_ha_32 RTL template variants (which now follow
Pmode == Pptr), but it incorrectly tied the choice of TLS base
register to the same predicate.

Under our default ILP32 hybrid ABI TARGET_64BIT is true and Pmode is
SImode.  The previous shape took the `else' branch and emitted

    addis  rX,2,sym@tprel@ha
    addi   rX,rX,sym@tprel@l

using r2 (the TOC pointer) as the supposed thread-pointer base.  The
PowerPC64 ELF ABI puts the thread pointer in r13 whenever the binary
is ELF64, regardless of how wide the C pointer model is.  Using r2
silently produces wrong-code: each thread-local access reads from the
caller's TOC instead of the calling thread's TLS area.

The two decisions are independent and need to be made on independent
predicates:

  * Which physical register holds the thread pointer is fixed by the
    target's ELF class.  For powerpc64-ps3-elf this is always r13;
    PowerPC 32-bit ELF uses r2.  Gate on TARGET_64BIT.

  * Which RTL template variant emits the addis/addi sequence depends
    on the operand width, i.e. Pmode (== Pptr).  Gate on
    Pmode == DImode.

This patch unconditionally sets `tlsreg' from TARGET_64BIT and then
selects the template variant by Pmode.  All other Pmode == DImode
checks in this file were already template-variant decisions and are
left unchanged.

No existing in-tree sample exercises a block-scope static
thread_local, so the wrong-code went undetected until EMP_Lib's
collisionResponse.cpp brought it to surface.  After the fix the same
TU emits

    addis  9,13,sym@tprel@ha
    addi   9,9,sym@tprel@l

which is the canonical ELFv1 ELF64 local-exec sequence.

--- a/gcc/config/rs6000/rs6000.cc
+++ b/gcc/config/rs6000/rs6000.cc
@@ -9544,16 +9544,15 @@
       rtx tlsreg, tmp;
 
       tmp = gen_reg_rtx (Pmode);
+      /* The TLS pointer register depends on the ELF class (TARGET_64BIT),
+	 not on C pointer width.  Under our ELF64 + ILP32 hybrid default,
+	 TARGET_64BIT is true while Pmode is SImode; the base register
+	 stays r13.  The RTL template variant still follows Pmode.  */
+      tlsreg = gen_rtx_REG (Pmode, TARGET_64BIT ? 13 : 2);
       if (Pmode == DImode)
-	{
-	  tlsreg = gen_rtx_REG (Pmode, 13);
-	  insn = gen_tls_tprel_ha_64 (tmp, tlsreg, addr);
-	}
+	insn = gen_tls_tprel_ha_64 (tmp, tlsreg, addr);
       else
-	{
-	  tlsreg = gen_rtx_REG (Pmode, 2);
-	  insn = gen_tls_tprel_ha_32 (tmp, tlsreg, addr);
-	}
+	insn = gen_tls_tprel_ha_32 (tmp, tlsreg, addr);
       emit_insn (insn);
       if (Pmode == DImode)
 	insn = gen_tls_tprel_lo_64 (dest, tmp, addr);
